Red Wine Quality Analysis

The dataset was created using red wine samples. The inputs include objective tests (e.g. PH values) and the output is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts). Each expert graded the wine quality between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

The dataset is related to red variants of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine. Due to privacy and logistic issues, only physicochemical (inputs) and sensory (the output) variables are available (e.g. there is no data about grape types, wine brand, wine selling price, etc.).

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

We have 1599 observations and 12 features in our data

All the test values are continuous, with varing ranges and the output quality is a scale: 0 ——-> 10 (Worst) (Best)

The dataset is biased as there are more observations for normal quality as for the good and poor ones. Interesting thing is the scale for quality is 0-10 but the min-max values for data are 3-8, no wine is very bad and none is exceptionally good.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature is the quality of wine. I’d like to determine what determines the quality of a wine.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The acids in our dataset and suger and salt(chloride) are the more likely candidates for the wine quality from what I understand about wines. the pH may depend upon the concentration of acids and the density on sugar content.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No I didn’t create new variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Most of the distributions were skewed with outliers towards max values. I log10, sqrt and cuberoot transformed or removed upper 1% values to plot in these distribuions. We know that we have very few good and poor wines. These outlier values may be related to these observations, which I would like to explore more in the next sections.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

The citric acid, sulphates and alcohol has a positive correlation with the quality of wine.

Volatile acids, density, residual sugar and chlorides have a negative correlation with the quality of wine.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features

(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

as the pH lowers the quality of wine increases, which means the wine becomes more acidic but we saw a negative correlation with volatile acids and positive for non volatile acids. this shows that the overall acidity of wine has a positive correlation with quality.

Most of the relationships are not directly linear, there is a behaviour change in relationship around level 7-8 or 3-4

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Citric acid, volatile acid, Chlorides and sulphates are in strong relation with quality of wine

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

In this graph we see the sulphates content vs the quality of wine. We see that as the sulphate content in wine increases the quality of wine also increases. the mean value shows a very linear relationship between the two values.

Plot Two

Description Two

In the first plot we see that good wines have the high citric acid value and also high fixed acid value.

In the second graph we observe that for a better quality wine the citric acid has high content value but the lower volatile content. These two acids have opposite trends for the quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

In both the plots we see the trends of previous plots. Also when the acid level is a constant the quality of wine increases as the alcohol content is increasing. This shows a strong positive correlation between alcohol and wine qulality.

Reflection

The citric acid can add “freshness” and flavour to a wine and we saw that the quality of wine increases with the increase in citric acid content in wine.

Similarly, the high value of volatile acid (acetic acid) can lead to unpleasant, vinegar taste and in our plot we observed that in high quality wine this acid content is low.

Also, the pH value is low in good wines, in other words, the acidity of wine is high in good quality wines.

In most cases, other values remains constant the increase in alcohol content increases the wine quality.

And, sugar, salt, density all have a negative relationships to wine quality

In the plots therse are too many outliers, as we know that the data is biased with more observations for normal wines, we may analyze those outlier values for the wine quality.
